body:
**Describe the bug**

AbstractAssert.satisfies(Consumer...)  executes each consumer twice if any of the consumer fail. It comes from statistiesForProxy implementation

```java
  protected SELF satisfiesForProxy(Consumer<? super ACTUAL>[] assertionsGroups) throws AssertionError {
    checkArgument(stream(assertionsGroups).allMatch(java.util.Objects::nonNull), "No assertions group should be null");
    if (stream(assertionsGroups).allMatch(this::satisfiesAssertions)) return myself;
    // some assertions groups were not met! let's report all the errors
    List<AssertionError> assertionErrors = stream(assertionsGroups).map(this::catchOptionalAssertionError)
                                                                   .filter(Optional::isPresent)
                                                                   .map(Optional::get)
                                                                   .collect(toList());
    throw multipleAssertionsError(assertionErrors);
  }
```

Executing the consumer twice is usually OK as most consumers are idempotent. However, some are not. I stumbled upon this is issue writing the following test involving a JAX-RS response

```java
              .run( webTarget -> {
                        var response = webTarget.get( );

                        assertThat( response )
                                .satisfies( isClientErrorWithMessage( "filter", "foo" ) );
                    } );


 Consumer<Response> isClientErrorWithMessage( String field, String... messageParts ) {
        return response -> {
            assertThat( response.getStatus( ) ).isEqualTo( 400 );

            var jsonResponse = response.readEntity( JsonNode.class );
            [...]
    }
```

A response can only be read once. `java.lang.IllegalStateException: Entity input stream has already been closed .` is displayed rather than the actual error. 
 
It seems easy to change satisfiesForProxy implementation to avoid the superfluous execution. I can try to submit a merge request if you acknowledge the issue and that my reasoning is correct. 

* assertj core version: 3.22.0
* java version: 17

**Test case reproducing the bug**

```java
    @Test
    void reproducer( ) {
        Consumer<String> consumer = s -> {
            System.out.println( s );
            assertThat( s ).isEqualTo( "bar" );
        };
        assertThat( "Foo" ).satisfies( consumer );
    }
```

```
Foo
Foo


expected: "bar"
 but was: "Foo"
Comparison Failure: 
Expected :"bar"
Actual   :"Foo"
```
